			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008</a> paper:</span><br><i>Sudoku – A Language Description Case Study</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TerjeGjøsæter.html">Terje Gjøsæter</a>, <a href="../profile/IngelinFIsfeldt.html">Ingelin F. Isfeldt</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreasPrinz.html">Andreas Prinz</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_19">10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_19</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6a.html"><span class="tagM">T6A: Experience Reports</span></a><ul><li> The ‘pearls’ framing makes it an experience-oriented report of language description practices.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It is presented as a language-description case study, focusing on describing/analyzing a language precisely.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The Sudoku language description is effectively a DSL case illustrating language engineering choices.
</li></ul></li></ul>
